    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1980-02-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1980-02-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="101"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d101">
                <head>101. Central Intelligence Agency Intelligence Information Cable<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d101fn1">Source: Carter Library, National Security
                        Affairs, Staff Material, Horn/Special, Box 4, 2–3/80. Secret; [<hi
                            rend="italic">handling restrictions not declassified</hi>]. Sent to the
                        White House Situation Room, Department of State, National Foreign Affairs
                        Center (<gloss target="#t_CIA_1">CIA</gloss>), <gloss target="#t_DIA_1"
                            >DIA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSA_1">NSA</gloss>, and Joint Chiefs of Staff.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <idno type="document-identifier">TDFIR 314/04093–80</idno>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1980-02-27">February 27, 1980</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>COUNTRY</head>
                    <item>Somalia/Ethiopia</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>President <persName corresp="#p_SBM_1">Siad</persName>’s Pledge for
                        Continued Support to the <gloss target="#t_WSLF_1">WSLF</gloss>. (<gloss
                            target="#t_DOI_1">DOI</gloss>: Mid-February 1980)</item>
                </list>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>SOURCE</head>
                    <item>[<hi rend="italic">4 lines not declassified</hi>]</item>
                </list>
                <p>1. Somali President <persName corresp="#p_SBM_1">Mohamed Siad Barre</persName>
                    called a meeting of Western Somali Liberation Front (<gloss target="#t_WSLF_1"
                        >WSLF</gloss>) leaders at the Somali militia training camp near Afgoi in
                    mid-February 1980 and assured them that Somali Government support to the <gloss
                        target="#t_WSLF_1">WSLF</gloss> would not be reduced even if Somalia signed
                    a military agreement with the United States. <persName corresp="#p_SBM_1"
                        >Siad</persName> had become concerned by reports in early February that
                        <gloss target="#t_WSLF_1">WSLF</gloss> leaders were worried that <persName
                        corresp="#p_SBM_1">Siad</persName> might reduce Somali Government support to
                    the <gloss target="#t_WSLF_1">WSLF</gloss> once an agreement with the United
                    States was signed. According to these reports, <gloss target="#t_WSLF_1"
                        >WSLF</gloss> leaders for the first time were discussing the possibility of
                    negotiating with the Ethiopians for autonomy rather than continuing the fight
                    for full independence. When <persName corresp="#p_SBM_1">Siad</persName> heard
                    these reports, he became very upset and ordered leading Somali officials from
                    the Ogadeni tribe, including Commandant of the Police, Brigadier General Adan
                    Abdi Duale, and Brigadier General Adan Abdullahi Nur, Commandant of the Halane
                    Political Indoctrination Institute for the Somali Revolutionary Socialist Party,
                    to arrange the meeting with <gloss target="#t_WSLF_1">WSLF</gloss> officials.
                    The meeting was attended by over 100 <gloss target="#t_WSLF_1">WSLF</gloss> and
                    Somali Government officials.</p>
                <p>2. (Field comment: Source did not know whether <persName corresp="#p_SBM_1"
                        >Siad</persName> specified that type of support the Somali Government would
                    continue to provide the <gloss target="#t_WSLF_1">WSLF</gloss>.)</p>
            </div>
